AWS storage 

What is an EBS volume? 
= it’s a type of block storage that you attach to an EC2 instance mainly ( Other container services/ repurpose snapshots )

                                                                                         
- Virtual (storage) hard drive like where you store data persistently                                            
- Even if the EC2 instance stops  , the EBS Volume stays intact 
- You can reattach it / or take a snapshot for backup 
- Good for storage of databases , logs , files etc 


* EBS restricted to a specific availability zone *
-> If you need in another zone ? -> create a snapshot and restore in that new zone 



What is an AMI ( amazon machine image ) ? 
= a template for launching an EC2 instance that includes and you can customise :
- An operating system 
- Software & configurations

You can launch EC2 instances from: 
- A public AMI : AWS provided 
- Your own AMI : make and maintain them yourself - great for replicating set ups 
- An AWS marketplace AMI : an AMI someone else made / sells 

pros of AMI ? 
→ allowing you to automate setup of EC2 instances
→ faster boot times as it’s pre-packaged
→ You can launch multiple ec2 instances as you have got the right configurations + snapshots 
→ saves time = when scaling infra , re-creating environments , launching instances in different regions 

* AMI are built for a specific region (can be copied across regions) * 

*when you spin up an EC2 you pick an AMI  to define what software stack it starts with*
*can use pre-built or build your own AMI *


What Is amazon EFS ( elastic file system ) ? 

Pros of EFS ? 

→ Managed network file system 
→ Can mount Multiple EC2 instances on it and can access it at the same time = highly available , reliable 
→ Works across EC2 instances in multi Availability zones 
→ Scales automatically with your data 
→ Can easily share data between themselves as they’re connected 


Cons of EFS ? 
- Expensive - 3x of SSD - really use it when app needs shared storage across multiple instances 
- Pay per use 
